Title: The Jungle Book
Credit: Written by
Author: Rudyard Kipling
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/21/2026
Notes: Period live-action jungle adventure; talking animals share one realistic medium with the human boy. Warm earth and leaf tones; moonlit blues at Council Rock; fire as the sole hard orange.

FADE IN:

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

Moonlight spills into a rocky den in the Seeonee hills. FATHER WOLF, a lean gray wolf, wakes from his day's rest, scratches, yawns, and spreads his paws one after another. MOTHER WOLF (RAKSHA), a great gray she-wolf, lies with her nose across FOUR WOLF CUBS who tumble and squeal against her flank.

FATHER WOLF
Augrh! It is time to hunt again.

He gathers to spring downhill. A little shadow with a bushy tail crosses the threshold—TABAQUI the jackal, mean-coated, eyes bright with mischief—and whines.

TABAQUI
Good luck go with you, O Chief of the Wolves. And good luck and strong white teeth go with noble children that they may never forget the hungry in this world.

FATHER WOLF
(stiffly)
Enter, then, and look, but there is no food here.

TABAQUI
For a wolf, no, but for so mean a person as myself a dry bone is a good feast. Who are we, the Gidur-log, to pick and choose?

He scuttles to the back, finds a buck bone with meat still on it, and cracks it merrily.

TABAQUI
All thanks for this good meal. How beautiful are the noble children! How large are their eyes! And so young too! Indeed, indeed, I might have remembered that the children of kings are men from the beginning.

Mother Wolf and Father Wolf look uncomfortable. Tabaqui rejoices in the mischief, then speaks spitefully.

TABAQUI
Shere Khan, the Big One, has shifted his hunting grounds. He will hunt among these hills for the next moon, so he has told me.

FATHER WOLF
He has no right! By the Law of the Jungle he has no right to change his quarters without due warning. He will frighten every head of game within ten miles, and I—I have to kill for two, these days.

MOTHER WOLF
His mother did not call him Lungri for nothing. He has been lame in one foot from his birth. That is why he has only killed cattle. Now the villagers of the Waingunga are angry with him, and he has come here to make our villagers angry. They will scour the jungle for him when he is far away, and we and our children must run when the grass is set alight. Indeed, we are very grateful to Shere Khan!

TABAQUI
Shall I tell him of your gratitude?

FATHER WOLF
Out! Out and hunt with thy master. Thou hast done harm enough for one night.

TABAQUI
I go. Ye can hear Shere Khan below in the thickets. I might have saved myself the message.

EXT. SEEONEE VALLEY - NIGHT

Below in the valley that runs to a little river: the dry, angry, snarly, singsong whine of a tiger who has caught nothing.

FATHER WOLF (O.S.)
The fool! To begin a night's work with that noise!

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

Father Wolf at the mouth. Mother Wolf lifts her head.

MOTHER WOLF
H'sh. It is neither bullock nor buck he hunts to-night. It is Man.

The whine becomes a humming purr from every quarter—then the full-throated aaooughh:

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
Aaarh!

A howl—untigerish. Father Wolf runs out a few paces.

FATHER WOLF
He has missed.

EXT. THICKET BELOW THE CAVE - NIGHT

SHERE KHAN, huge lame tiger, tumbles in the scrub, muttering, feet scorched. Tabaqui dances near him.

FATHER WOLF (O.S.)
The fool has had no more sense than to jump at a woodcutter's campfire, and has burned his feet. Tabaqui is with him.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

MOTHER WOLF
Something is coming uphill. Get ready.

EXT. CAVE MOUTH / THICKET - NIGHT

Bushes rustle. Father Wolf drops on his haunches, ready to leap—then checks in mid-spring, shoots straight up four or five feet, and lands almost where he left ground.

FATHER WOLF
Man! A man's cub. Look!

Directly in front of him, holding a low branch: a naked brown baby who can just walk—soft, dimpled. BABY MOWGLI looks up into Father Wolf's face and laughs.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

MOTHER WOLF
Is that a man's cub? I have never seen one. Bring it here.

Father Wolf mouths the child without breaking the skin and lays him among the cubs. Baby Mowgli pushes between them toward the warm hide.

MOTHER WOLF
How little! How naked, and—how bold! Ahai! He is taking his meal with the others. And so this is a man's cub. Now, was there ever a wolf that could boast of a man's cub among her children?

FATHER WOLF
I have heard now and again of such a thing, but never in our Pack or in my time. He is altogether without hair, and I could kill him with a touch of my foot. But see, he looks up and is not afraid.

Moonlight at the mouth is blocked. Shere Khan's great square head and shoulders thrust into the entrance. Tabaqui squeaks behind him.

TABAQUI
My lord, my lord, it went in here!

FATHER WOLF
Shere Khan does us great honor. What does Shere Khan need?

His eyes are very angry. The cave mouth is too narrow for the tiger; Shere Khan's shoulders and forepaws are cramped.

SHERE KHAN
My quarry. A man's cub went this way. Its parents have run off. Give it to me.

FATHER WOLF
The Wolves are a free people. They take orders from the Head of the Pack, and not from any striped cattle-killer. The man's cub is ours—to kill if we choose.

SHERE KHAN
Ye choose and ye do not choose! What talk is this of choosing? By the bull that I killed, am I to stand nosing into your dog's den for my fair dues? It is I, Shere Khan, who speak!

His roar fills the cave with thunder. Mother Wolf shakes free of the cubs and springs forward—eyes like two green moons facing his blaze.

MOTHER WOLF
And it is I, Raksha, who answers. The man's cub is mine, Lungri—mine to me! He shall not be killed. He shall live to run with the Pack and to hunt with the Pack; and in the end, look you, hunter of little naked cubs—frog-eater—fish-killer—he shall hunt thee! Now get hence, or by the Sambhur that I killed, back thou goest to thy mother, burned beast of the jungle, lamer than ever thou camest into the world! Go!

Shere Khan backs out growling. Clear of the mouth, he shouts:

SHERE KHAN
Each dog barks in his own yard! We will see what the Pack will say to this fostering of man-cubs. The cub is mine, and to my teeth he will come in the end, O bush-tailed thieves!

Mother Wolf throws herself down panting among the cubs.

FATHER WOLF
Shere Khan speaks this much truth. The cub must be shown to the Pack. Wilt thou still keep him, Mother?

MOTHER WOLF
Keep him! He came naked, by night, alone and very hungry; yet he was not afraid! Look, he has pushed one of my babes to one side already. And that lame butcher would have killed him and would have run off to the Waingunga while the villagers here hunted through all our lairs in revenge! Keep him? Assuredly I will keep him. Lie still, little frog. O thou Mowgli—for Mowgli the Frog I will call thee—the time will come when thou wilt hunt Shere Khan as he has hunted thee.

FATHER WOLF
But what will our Pack say?

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Full moon. A hilltop of stones and boulders. AKELA, great gray Lone Wolf, lies full length on his rock. Below him, forty or more wolves of every size and color. Cubs tumble in the center. Senior wolves pad up, inspect, return. Anxious mothers push cubs into the moonlight.

AKELA
Ye know the Law—ye know the Law. Look well, O Wolves!

WOLF MOTHERS
Look—look well, O Wolves!

Father Wolf and Mother Wolf arrive with their cubs and young MOWGLI THE FROG. Father Wolf pushes Mowgli into the center. The child sits laughing, playing with pebbles that glisten in the moonlight.

AKELA
Look well!

A muffled roar from behind the rocks—Shere Khan.

SHERE KHAN
The cub is mine. Give him to me. What have the Free People to do with a man's cub?

AKELA
Look well, O Wolves! What have the Free People to do with the orders of any save the Free People? Look well!

Deep growls. A YOUNG WOLF in his fourth year flings the question back.

YOUNG WOLF
What have the Free People to do with a man's cub?

AKELA
Who speaks for this cub? Among the Free People who speaks?

No answer. Mother Wolf gathers herself for a last fight.

BALOO, a sleepy brown bear, rises on his hindquarters and grunts.

BALOO
The man's cub—the man's cub? I speak for the man's cub. There is no harm in a man's cub. I have no gift of words, but I speak the truth. Let him run with the Pack, and be entered with the others. I myself will teach him.

AKELA
We need yet another. Baloo has spoken, and he is our teacher for the young cubs. Who speaks besides Baloo?

A black shadow drops into the circle—BAGHEERA the Black Panther, inky black, moon-marks like watered silk on his fur, soft as wild rose-leaves, deadlier than the wolves.

BAGHEERA
O Akela, and ye the Free People, I have no right in your assembly, but the Law of the Jungle says that if there is a doubt which is not a killing matter in regard to a new cub, the life of that cub may be bought at a price. And the Law does not say who may or may not pay that price. Am I right?

AKELA
Good! Good! It is the Law. Also, the cub is still without a price on his head. Baloo has spoken, and Bagheera has spoken. Now to Baloo's word I will add one bull, and a fat one, newly killed, not half a mile from here, if ye will accept the man's cub according to the Law. Is it difficult?

A clamor of voices. The Pack takes the bull. Mowgli is free to run with the Pack.

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
He may do his best, but he will not always keep his man-cub!

BAGHEERA
(softly, to Mother Wolf)
It was well done. Men and their cubs are very wise. He may be a help in time.

MOTHER WOLF
He is mine! Mine to me! He shall live to run with the Pack and in the end he shall hunt thee, Lungri!

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And that is how Mowgli was entered into the Seeonee Wolf Pack at the price of a bull and on Baloo's good word. Now you must be content to skip ten or eleven whole years, and only guess at all the wonderful life that Mowgli led among the wolves, because if it were written out it would fill ever so many books.

EXT. SEEONEE JUNGLE GLADE - DAY

Sun filters through heavy green. BALOO, a big serious old brown bear, sits on his haunches. Young MOWGLI stands before him, bare and brown, reciting. BAGHEERA lounges against a tree-trunk, purring, head pressed to the bark.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
All that is told here happened some time before Mowgli was turned out of the Seeonee Wolf Pack, or revenged himself on Shere Khan. It was in the days when Baloo was teaching him the Law of the Jungle.

MOWGLI
Feet that make no noise; eyes that can see in the dark; ears that can hear the winds in their lairs, and sharp white teeth—all these things are the marks of our brothers except Tabaqui the Jackal and the Hyaena whom we hate.

BALOO
Again. And the Wood and Water Laws. How to tell a rotten branch from a sound one. How to speak politely to the wild bees. What to say to Mang the Bat. How to warn the water-snakes before thou splashest down.

Mowgli sighs, climbs a low branch, drops, runs a circle, swims a hand through a pool's edge as if rehearsing.

BAGHEERA
(soft, amused)
How small he is. How can his little head carry all thy long talk?

BALOO
Is there anything in the jungle too little to be killed? No. That is why I teach him these things, and that is why I hit him, very softly, when he forgets.

BAGHEERA
Softly! What dost thou know of softness, old Iron-feet? His face is all bruised today by thy—softness. Ugh.

BALOO
Better he should be bruised from head to foot by me who love him than that he should come to harm through ignorance. I am now teaching him the Master Words of the Jungle that shall protect him with the birds and the Snake People, and all that hunt on four feet, except his own pack. Is not that worth a little beating?

BAGHEERA
Well, look to it then that thou dost not kill the man-cub. He is no tree trunk to sharpen thy blunt claws upon. But what are those Master Words? I should like to know.

BALOO
I will call Mowgli and he shall say them—if he will. Come, Little Brother!

A sullen little voice from high above.

MOWGLI (O.S.)
My head is ringing like a bee tree.

Mowgli slides down a trunk, angry and indignant.

MOWGLI
I come for Bagheera and not for thee, fat old Baloo!

BALOO
(hurt, quiet)
That is all one to me. Tell Bagheera, then, the Master Words of the Jungle that I have taught thee this day.

MOWGLI
(delighted to show off)
Master Words for which people? The jungle has many tongues. I know them all.

BALOO
A little thou knowest, but not much. See, O Bagheera, they never thank their teacher. Say the word for the Hunting-People, then—great scholar.

MOWGLI
(Bear accent)
We be of one blood, ye and I.

BALOO
Good. Now for the birds.

Mowgli repeats it with a kite's whistle at the end.

BAGHEERA
Now for the Snake-People.

Mowgli answers with a long, perfect hiss. He kicks up his heels, claps, jumps sideways onto Bagheera's back, drums with his heels on the glossy hide, and makes faces at Baloo.

BALOO
(tender)
There—there! That was worth a little bruise. Some day thou wilt remember me.

Baloo turns to Bagheera, proud, patting his furry stomach.

BALOO
Hathi the Wild Elephant gave me the Words. He took Mowgli to a pool for the Snake Word, for I could not pronounce it. Neither snake, bird, nor beast will hurt him now. No one then is to be feared.

BAGHEERA
(under his breath)
Except his own tribe.
(aloud)
Have a care for my ribs, Little Brother! What is all this dancing up and down?

Mowgli pulls Bagheera's shoulder fur, kicks, shouting.

MOWGLI
And so I shall have a tribe of my own, and lead them through the branches all day long.

BAGHEERA
What is this new folly, little dreamer of dreams?

MOWGLI
Yes, and throw branches and dirt at old Baloo. They have promised me this. Ah!

Baloo's big paw scoops Mowgli off Bagheera. The boy lies between the Bear's forepaws. Baloo is angry.

BALOO
Mowgli, thou hast been talking with the Bandar-log—the Monkey People.

Mowgli looks to Bagheera. The panther's eyes are hard as jade.

BAGHEERA
Thou hast been with the Monkey People—the gray apes—the people without a law—the eaters of everything. That is great shame.

MOWGLI
(snuffling)
When Baloo hurt my head, I went away, and the gray apes came down from the trees and had pity on me. No one else cared.

BALOO
The pity of the Monkey People! The stillness of the mountain stream! The cool of the summer sun! And then, man-cub?

MOWGLI
And then they gave me nuts and pleasant things to eat, and they carried me in their arms up to the top of the trees and said I was their blood brother except that I had no tail, and should be their leader some day.

BAGHEERA
They have no leader. They lie. They have always lied.

MOWGLI
They were very kind and bade me come again. Why have I never been taken among the Monkey People? They stand on their feet as I do. They do not hit me with their hard paws. They play all day. Let me get up! Bad Baloo, let me up! I will play with them again.

BALOO
(voice like thunder)
Listen, man-cub. I have taught thee all the Law of the Jungle for all the peoples of the jungle—except the Monkey-Folk who live in the trees. They have no law. They are outcasts. They have no speech of their own, but use the stolen words which they overhear when they listen, and peep, and wait up above in the branches. Their way is not our way. They are without leaders. They have no remembrance. They boast and chatter and pretend that they are a great people about to do great affairs in the jungle, but the falling of a nut turns their minds to laughter and all is forgotten. We of the jungle have no dealings with them. We do not drink where the monkeys drink; we do not go where the monkeys go; we do not hunt where they hunt; we do not die where they die. Hast thou ever heard me speak of the Bandar-log till today?

MOWGLI
(whisper)
No.

BALOO
The Jungle-People put them out of their mouths and out of their minds. They are very many, evil, dirty, shameless, and they desire, if they have any fixed desire, to be noticed by the Jungle People. But we do not notice them even when they throw nuts and filth on our heads.

A shower of nuts and twigs spatters down through the branches. Coughings, howlings, angry jumpings high among the thin limbs.

BALOO
The Monkey-People are forbidden—forbidden to the Jungle-People. Remember.

BAGHEERA
Forbidden. But I still think Baloo should have warned thee against them.

BALOO
I—I? How was I to guess he would play with such dirt. The Monkey People! Faugh!

A fresh shower. Baloo and Bagheera trot away, taking Mowgli with them.

EXT. JUNGLE UNDERSTORY - DAY

High above, gray shapes of the BANDAR-LOG watch, whisper, invent a plan among themselves. Below, Mowgli walks ashamed between Bear and Panther.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The monkeys never meant to do any more—the Bandar-log never mean anything at all. But one invented a brilliant idea: Mowgli could weave sticks together. If they caught him, they could make him teach them. This time, they said, they were really going to have a leader.

EXT. JUNGLE NAP PLACE - MIDDAY

Mowgli sleeps between Bagheera and Baloo, resolving to have no more to do with the Monkey People. Hard strong little hands seize his legs and arms. A swash of branches in his face.

Baloo wakes the jungle with deep cries. Bagheera bounds up a trunk, every tooth bared. The Bandar-log howl with triumph and scuffle to the upper branches where the panther dare not follow.

BANDAR-LOG
He has noticed us! Bagheera has noticed us. All the Jungle-People admire us for our skill and our cunning.

Two strong monkeys catch Mowgli under the arms and swing off through the treetops, twenty feet at a bound. The whole tribe sweeps along the tree-roads with Mowgli their prisoner.

EXT. JUNGLE TREETOPS - DAY

Bounding, crashing, whooping. Mowgli sick and giddy, yet half enjoying the wild rush—earth far below, the terrible check and jerk over empty air. Branches lash his face. Miles of still green jungle open and close.

He stares upward. Far in the blue, RANN THE KITE balances and wheels.

Mowgli gives the Kite call.

MOWGLI
We be of one blood, thou and I!

Rann drops a few hundred yards, whistles with surprise.

MOWGLI
Mark my trail! Tell Baloo of the Seeonee Pack and Bagheera of the Council Rock.

RANN
In whose name, Brother?

MOWGLI
Mowgli, the Frog. Man-cub they call me! Mark my trail!

Shrieked as he is swung through air. Rann nods, rises till he is a speck, watching the swaying treetops with telescope eyes.

RANN
They never go far. They never do what they set out to do. Always pecking at new things are the Bandar-log. The boy will be dropped in an old city. I know that road.

EXT. JUNGLE FLOOR - DAY

Baloo and Bagheera crash through undergrowth, furious and spent. Rann stoops and cries the news.

RANN
He has gone toward the Cold Lairs—the lost city. The Bandar-log have him.

BAGHEERA
Beyond the river. We must have help. Kaa!

BALOO
The big Rock Python. He can climb where we cannot. Come!

EXT. WARM ROCKS ABOVE THE RIVER - DAY

KAA, a huge rock-python thirty feet long, lies sunning, newly changed coat gleaming. Baloo and Bagheera approach with respect.

BALOO
Good hunting, Kaa!

KAA
Good hunting for us all. What makes ye so hot and breathless?

BAGHEERA
The Bandar-log have stolen our man-cub. We need thy wisdom and thy strength.

KAA
(eyes brightening)
The Monkey-People. I have a quarrel with them of old. They threw sticks and nuts and mocked my new skin. Where have they taken him?

BALOO
To the Cold Lairs.

KAA
I will come with thee. Softly, softly. The Bandar-log fear me more than fire or Bagheera.

EXT. COLD LAIRS - DUSK

Ruined city swallowed by jungle: broken domes, terraces, a great reservoir tank, marble summerhouse with pierced screen-work. Bandar-log pour over walls with Mowgli, chattering of kings and laws they will make.

MOWGLI
(calling Master Words)
We be of one blood, ye and I!

COBRAS in the summerhouse dust recoil and answer. Mowgli is thrust inside the ruined summerhouse; the monkeys bar the broken door with sticks and dance outside.

BANDAR-LOG
We are great. We are free. We will make a leader of the man-cub!

EXT. COLD LAIRS TERRACE AND RESERVOIR - NIGHT

Baloo and Bagheera burst from the jungle. Monkeys scream and fling themselves upon them. Bagheera fights toward the tank; Baloo stands like a rock under a rain of biting, scratching bodies.

BAGHEERA
To the water tank! They will not follow!

Bagheera plunges into the reservoir. Baloo is half buried under monkeys. From the dark, Kaa arrives—silent, enormous.

KAA
(one long hissing word)

Far-off monkeys freeze on loaded branches. The city falls still. Then clamor breaks again—monkeys leap higher, cling to stone idols, shriek along the battlements.

Inside the summerhouse screenwork, Mowgli dances and hoots owl-fashion between his teeth.

BAGHEERA
(gasping)
Get the man-cub out of that trap; I can do no more. Let us take the man-cub and go. They may attack again.

KAA
They will not move till I order them. Stay you sssso!

Silence clamps the city once more.

KAA
I could not come before, Brother, but I think I heard thee call.

BAGHEERA
I—I may have cried out in the battle. Baloo, art thou hurt?

BALOO
(shaking one leg after another)
I am not sure that they did not pull me into a hundred little bearlings. Wow! I am sore. Kaa, we owe thee, I think, our lives—Bagheera and I.

KAA
No matter. Where is the manling?

MOWGLI (O.S.)
Here, in a trap. I cannot climb out.

INT. COLD LAIRS SUMMERHOUSE - NIGHT

The curve of the broken dome hangs above Mowgli. Cobras recoil in the dust.

COBRAS
Take him away. He dances like Mao the Peacock. He will crush our young.

EXT. COLD LAIRS TERRACE AND RESERVOIR - NIGHT

Kaa chuckles, head swaying.

KAA
Hah! He has friends everywhere, this manling. Stand back, manling. And hide you, O Poison People. I break down the wall.

Kaa finds a discolored crack in the marble tracery. Two or three light taps for distance—then six feet of body lifts clear and smashes home, nose-first, half a dozen full-power blows.

Screen-work explodes in dust and rubbish. Mowgli leaps through and flings himself between Baloo and Bagheera—an arm around each big neck.

BALOO
(hugging him softly)
Art thou hurt?

MOWGLI
I am sore, hungry, and not a little bruised. But, oh, they have handled ye grievously, my Brothers! Ye bleed.

BAGHEERA
(licking his lips, eyeing monkey-dead)
Others also.

BALOO
(whimpering)
It is nothing, it is nothing, if thou art safe, oh, my pride of all little frogs!

BAGHEERA
(dry)
Of that we shall judge later. But here is Kaa to whom we owe the battle and thou owest thy life. Thank him according to our customs, Mowgli.

Mowgli turns. The great Python's head sways a foot above his own—scarred nose, enormous coils, cool strength.

KAA
So this is the manling. Very soft is his skin, and he is not unlike the Bandar-log. Have a care, manling, that I do not mistake thee for a monkey some twilight when I have newly changed my coat.

MOWGLI
We be one blood, thou and I. I take my life from thee tonight. My kill shall be thy kill if ever thou art hungry, O Kaa.

KAA
(eyes twinkling)
All thanks, Little Brother. And what may so bold a hunter kill? I ask that I may follow when next he goes abroad.

MOWGLI
I kill nothing,—I am too little,—but I drive goats toward such as can use them. When thou art empty come to me and see if I speak the truth. I have some skill in these—

He holds out his hands.

MOWGLI
—and if ever thou art in a trap, I may pay the debt which I owe to thee, to Bagheera, and to Baloo, here. Good hunting to ye all, my masters.

BALOO
(growling approval)
Well said.

Kaa drops his head lightly on Mowgli's shoulder.

KAA
A brave heart and a courteous tongue. They shall carry thee far through the jungle, manling. But now go hence quickly with thy friends. Go and sleep, for the moon sets, and what follows it is not well that thou shouldst see.

The moon sinks behind the hills. Lines of trembling monkeys huddle on walls like ragged fringes. Baloo drinks at the tank. Bagheera sets his fur in order.

Kaa glides to the center of the terrace and brings his jaws together with a ringing snap. Every monkey eye locks on him.

KAA
The moon sets. Is there yet light enough to see?

BANDAR-LOG
(from the walls, a moan like wind)
We see, O Kaa.

KAA
Good. Begins now the dance—the Dance of the Hunger of Kaa. Sit still and watch.

Kaa turns twice or thrice in a big circle, weaving his head. Loops and figures of eight—soft oozy triangles melting into squares and five-sided figures, coiled mounds—never resting, never hurrying. A low humming song. Darker and darker until the coils vanish; only the rustle of scales remains.

Baloo and Bagheera stand still as stone, growling, neck-hair bristling. Mowgli watches and wonders.

KAA (O.S.)
Bandar-log, can ye stir foot or hand without my order? Speak!

BANDAR-LOG
Without thy order we cannot stir foot or hand, O Kaa!

KAA (O.S.)
Good! Come all one pace nearer to me.

The monkey lines sway forward helplessly. Baloo and Bagheera take one stiff step with them.

KAA (O.S.)
Nearer!

All move again. Mowgli lays his hands on Baloo and Bagheera. The two great beasts start as if waked from a dream.

BAGHEERA
(whispering)
Keep thy hand on my shoulder. Keep it there, or I must go back—must go back to Kaa. Aah!

MOWGLI
It is only old Kaa making circles on the dust. Let us go.

The three slip off through a gap in the walls toward the jungle. Behind them the rustle and the humming song go on.

EXT. JUNGLE OUTSIDE COLD LAIRS - NIGHT

Under still trees. Baloo shakes himself all over.

BALOO
Whoof! Never more will I make an ally of Kaa.

BAGHEERA
(trembling)
He knows more than we. In a little time, had I stayed, I should have walked down his throat.

BALOO
Many will walk by that road before the moon rises again. He will have good hunting—after his own fashion.

MOWGLI
But what was the meaning of it all? I saw no more than a big snake making foolish circles till the dark came. And his nose was all sore. Ho! Ho!

BAGHEERA
(angrily)
Mowgli, his nose was sore on thy account, as my ears and sides and paws, and Baloo's neck and shoulders are bitten on thy account. Neither Baloo nor Bagheera will be able to hunt with pleasure for many days.

BALOO
It is nothing; we have the man-cub again.

BAGHEERA
True, but he has cost us heavily in time which might have been spent in good hunting, in wounds, in hair—I am half plucked along my back—and last of all, in honor. For, remember, Mowgli, I, who am the Black Panther, was forced to call upon Kaa for protection, and Baloo and I were both made stupid as little birds by the Hunger Dance. All this, man-cub, came of thy playing with the Bandar-log.

MOWGLI
(sorrowfully)
True, it is true. I am an evil man-cub, and my stomach is sad in me.

BAGHEERA
Mf! What says the Law of the Jungle, Baloo?

BALOO
(mumbling, reluctant)
Sorrow never stays punishment. But remember, Bagheera, he is very little.

BAGHEERA
I will remember. But he has done mischief, and blows must be dealt now. Mowgli, hast thou anything to say?

MOWGLI
Nothing. I did wrong. Baloo and thou art wounded. It is just.

Bagheera delivers half a dozen love-taps—gentle for a panther, a hard beating for a seven-year-old boy. When it is over Mowgli sneezes and picks himself up without a word.

BAGHEERA
Now, jump on my back, Little Brother, and we will go home.

Mowgli lays his head on Bagheera's back and sleeps as they move into the dark.

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Years later. Akela is old; his leadership fails. Young wolves, fed by Shere Khan's flattery, turn on the Lone Wolf. Mowgli, nearly grown, stands among them with a branch of the Red Flower—fire—stolen from the village.

SHERE KHAN
The man-cub has lived too long. Give him to me.

AKELA
He has eaten our food. He has slept with us. He has driven game for us. He is our brother in all but blood.

YOUNG WOLF
He is a man! A man!

MOWGLI
(holding the blazing branch)
Ye have told me so often tonight that I am a man that I feel your words are true. So I do not call ye my brothers any more, but sag, dogs, as a man should. I go from you to my own people—if they be my own people. The jungle is shut to me, and I must forget your talk and your companionship. But I will be more merciful than ye are. Because I was all but your brother in blood, I promise that when I am a man among men I will not betray ye to men as ye have betrayed me. I call on Bagheera and Baloo and those who took my part tonight. I sleep no more in your lairs. The jungle is shut to me. But I will come again. And when I come, it will be to lay out Shere Khan's hide upon the Council Rock. Keep ye to your own trails. I go.

He flings the fire among them. Wolves scatter yelping. Bagheera and Mother Wolf press close. Mowgli weeps as only a man-cub can.

MOTHER WOLF
Come soon, little naked son of mine. For, listen, child of man, I loved thee more than ever I loved my cubs.

MOWGLI
I will surely come. And when I come it will be to lay Shere Khan's hide upon the Council Rock. Do not forget me! Tell them in the jungle never to forget me!

EXT. ROUGH VALLEY ROAD - DAY

Mowgli, bare and scarred, jogs steadily along a rough road down the valley—twenty miles of dust and heat.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
When Mowgli left the wolf's cave after the fight with the Pack at the Council Rock, he went down to the plowed lands where the villagers lived. He would not stop near the jungle fringe, because he knew that he had made at least one bad enemy at the Council.

EXT. GREAT PLAIN AND VILLAGE GATE - DAY

The valley opens into a great plain dotted with rocks and cut by ravines. At one end a little village; at the other the thick jungle stops as if cut with a hoe. Cattle and buffaloes graze. Herd-boys shout and run. Yellow pariah dogs bark.

Mowgli walks on, hungry. At the village gate the big thorn-bush barricade is pushed aside.

MOWGLI
Umph! So men are afraid of the People of the Jungle here also.

He sits by the gate. A VILLAGE MAN comes out. Mowgli stands, opens his mouth, points down it—food. The man stares and runs shouting up the single street.

PRIEST—big, fat, white clothes, red-and-yellow mark on his forehead—comes with a crowd of a hundred. They stare, talk, shout, point.

MESSUA, a kind-faced woman, pushes forward, eyes wet.

MESSUA
Nathoo! Nathoo! My son that was taken by the tiger long ago—look, look!

PRIEST
He is a wolf-child come from the jungle. Give him food, Messua, and we will see.

INT. MESSUA'S HUT - NIGHT

Messua feeds Mowgli milk and bread, dresses him in cloth, tries to comb his hair. He endures it, learning the names of things.

MESSUA
My husband's name is not Nathoo, but he will be a father to thee. Sleep, little son.

EXT. VILLAGE GRAZING GROUNDS - DAY

Months pass. Mowgli becomes a herd-boy among the buffaloes. GRAY BROTHER, one of Mother Wolf's cubs, slips from the jungle fringe to speak with him.

GRAY BROTHER
Shere Khan has come back to hunt thee. He lies up in the big ravines by the Waingunga. He means to kill.

MOWGLI
I am ready. Bring Akela if he will come. We will use the buffalo herd.

EXT. WAINGUNGA RAVINE MOUTH - DAY

Mowgli divides the herd—Akela taking the big bulls one way, Gray Brother the cows and calves the other—trapping Shere Khan, heavy with a village meal, in the narrow ravine. Buffaloes thunder. Dust. The lame tiger cannot climb the walls.

MOWGLI
Stamp, Rama! Stamp!

The herd pours over Shere Khan. When the dust settles, the tiger is dead under the bulls' hooves. Mowgli skins him with a knife borrowed from the village, working through the long hot afternoon while kites circle.

EXT. VILLAGE GATE - TWILIGHT

Mowgli comes toward the village with Shere Khan's hide on his head. BULDEO the hunter meets him, tries to take the skin for the reward, is mocked by Mowgli and sent packing by Akela's growl. Stones begin to fly from the villagers.

VILLAGERS
More sorcery! He can turn bullets. Buldeo, that was thy buffalo. Wolf! Wolf's cub!

MOWGLI
(bewildered)
Now what is this?

AKELA
(sitting composedly)
They are not unlike the Pack, these brothers of thine. It is in my head that, if bullets mean anything, they would cast thee out.

PRIEST
(waving a sprig of sacred tulsi)
Wolf! Wolf's cub! Go away!

MOWGLI
Again? Last time it was because I was a man. This time it is because I am a wolf. Let us go, Akela.

Messua breaks from the crowd and runs across to the herd.

MESSUA
Oh, my son, my son! They say thou art a sorcerer who can turn himself into a beast at will. I do not believe, but go away or they will kill thee. Buldeo says thou art a wizard, but I know thou hast avenged Nathoo's death.

VILLAGERS
Come back, Messua! Come back, or we will stone thee.

A stone strikes Mowgli in the mouth. He laughs a short, ugly laugh; blood on his lip.

MOWGLI
Run back, Messua. This is one of the foolish tales they tell under the big tree at dusk. I have at least paid for thy son's life. Farewell; and run quickly, for I shall send the herd in more swiftly than their brickbats. I am no wizard, Messua. Farewell!

Messua flees back toward the houses.

MOWGLI
Now, once more, Akela. Bring the herd in.

Akela's yell cracks across the plain. The buffaloes charge the gate like a whirlwind, scattering villagers right and left.

MOWGLI
(scornfully)
Keep count! It may be that I have stolen one of them. Keep count, for I will do your herding no more. Fare you well, children of men, and thank Messua that I do not come in with my wolves and hunt you up and down your street.

He turns on his heel and walks away with Akela into the darkening plain.

EXT. PLAIN BY WAINGUNGA RAVINE - NIGHT

Mowgli looks up at the stars. He and Akela move at a steady pace. Gray Brother joins them. The great striped hide is rolled into a bundle on Mowgli's head.

MOWGLI
No more sleeping in traps for me, Akela. Let us get Shere Khan's skin and go away. No, we will not hurt the village, for Messua was kind to me.

Moonlight turns the plain milky white. Far behind, temple bells bang and conches blare. Messua's distant weeping carries on the wind.

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Moon nearly down. Mowgli, Akela, and Gray Brother climb the hill and stop at the mouth of Mother Wolf's cave. Mowgli still bears the bundled hide.

MOWGLI
(shouting)
They have cast me out from the Man-Pack, Mother, but I come with the hide of Shere Khan to keep my word.

MOTHER WOLF walks stiffly from the cave, cubs behind her. Her eyes glow at the sight of the skin.

MOTHER WOLF
I told him on that day, when he crammed his head and shoulders into this cave, hunting for thy life, Little Frog—I told him that the hunter would be the hunted. It is well done.

BAGHEERA
(from the thicket, deep)
Little Brother, it is well done. We were lonely in the jungle without thee.

Bagheera runs to Mowgli's bare feet. They clamber up the Council Rock together. Mowgli spreads Shere Khan's striped hide on the flat stone where Akela used to sit, pegs it with four bamboo slivers. Akela lies down upon it.

AKELA
Look—look well, O Wolves.

From habit the Pack answers. Lame wolves, shot-wounded wolves, mangy wolves—many missing—drag themselves to the Rock. They stare at the striped hide, huge claws dangling from empty feet.

Mowgli leaps upon the rattling skin. He beats time with his heels and shouts the song that rises in his throat. Gray Brother and Akela howl between the verses.

MOWGLI
Look well, O Wolves! Have I kept my word?

The Pack bays yes. A tattered wolf lifts his head.

TATTERED WOLF
Lead us again, O Akela. Lead us again, O Man-cub, for we be sick of this lawlessness, and we would be the Free People once more.

BAGHEERA
(purring)
Nay, that may not be. When ye are full-fed, the madness may come upon you again. Not for nothing are ye called the Free People. Ye fought for freedom, and it is yours. Eat it, O Wolves.

MOWGLI
Man-Pack and Wolf-Pack have cast me out. Now I will hunt alone in the jungle.

GRAY BROTHER
And we will hunt with thee.

The four cubs press close about Mowgli's legs. Bagheera's eyes shine. Beyond the Rock the jungle waits, dark and open.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And that is the last of the Mowgli tales in this book. Now hear another story from another sea.

EXT. BERING SEA - DAY

Gray cold water under a low sky. Fog banks. A tiny Winter Wren clings exhausted to steamer rigging, then is cupped in human hands and carried below.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
All these things happened several years ago at a place called Novastoshnah, or North East Point, on the Island of St. Paul, away and away in the Bering Sea. Limmershin, the Winter Wren, told me the tale.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Miles of basalt rock and sand drowned in seals—hundreds of thousands. Bulls roar and fight in the breakers and on the nurseries. Surf dotted with heads hurrying ashore. From Hutchinson's Hill the beach is a living carpet of fur three and a half miles long. Fog hangs thick; when the sun breaks, everything turns pearly and rainbow-colored.

SEA CATCH—fifteen years old, huge gray fur seal, nearly a mane on his shoulders, long wicked dog-teeth, scarred all over—fights for his place. MATKAH, his gentle wife, comes ashore to him. Soon a white pup is born among the dark ones: KOTICK, the White Seal.

MATKAH
He is white! White as the ice. Sea Catch, look!

SEA CATCH
(gruff)
The first I ever saw. Swim soon, little one. The beaches are no place for dreamers.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Years pass in quick turns of fog and sun. Kotick grows—still pure white, a marvel. He plays with the holluschickie, the bachelor seals. He watches men come in boats, drive young seals, and club them on the killing-grounds. Blood on the sand. Kotick alone will not go quietly.

KOTICK
This is not the Law. There must be a place where men never come.

MATKAH
There is no such place. Swim and grow fat, and do not think too much.

EXT. OPEN SEA AND FAR BEACHES - DAY

Kotick swims thousands of miles—year after year—searching. He asks sea birds, sharks, walruses. He visits beaches from California to Japan. Everywhere: seals, and the shadow of the sealers.

KOTICK
Is there no place left?

An old SEA LION shrugs. A WALRUS grumbles of ice only. At last Kotick meets the great lazy SEA COW—manatee-like, slow, wise in currents—who leads him without words under a cliff.

EXT. UNDERSEA CLIFF TUNNEL - DAY

Dark water. Kotick follows the Sea Cow through a long drowned tunnel beneath the cliffs, lungs burning, until—

EXT. SEA COW BEACHES - DAY

Kotick bursts up gasping and puffing into open water at the farther end of the tunnel. Beyond him: the finest beaches he has ever seen—long stretches of smooth-worn rock fitted for seal-nurseries, hard sand sloping inland, rollers, long grass, sand dunes half hidden in beautiful rolling fog.

KOTICK
My wig! It was a long dive, but it was worth it.

He swims the edges, tasting the water. No men have ever come here. He checks the fishing, counts low sandy islands, and looks seaward to bars and shoals and rocks that would smash a ship six miles out. Between islands and mainland, deep water runs up to perpendicular cliffs—somewhere below them, the tunnel mouth.

KOTICK
It's Novastoshnah over again, but ten times better. Sea Cow must be wiser than I thought. Men can't come down the cliffs, even if there were any men; and the shoals to seaward would knock a ship to splinters. If any place in the sea is safe, this is it.

He explores thoroughly—every beach, every shoal—so he can answer all questions. Then he dives, finds the tunnel mouth again, and races south.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Six days later. Kotick hauls out just above Sea Lion's Neck. The seal who has been waiting for him meets him first. She sees by the look in his eyes that he has found his island at last.

The holluschickie, Sea Catch, and the other seals gather as he tells them. They laugh. A YOUNG SEAL about Kotick's age twists his head from side to side—newly married, making a great fuss.

YOUNG SEAL
This is all very well, Kotick, but you can't come from no one knows where and order us off like this. Remember we've been fighting for our nurseries, and that's a thing you never did. You preferred prowling about in the sea.

The others laugh with him.

KOTICK
I've no nursery to fight for. I only want to show you all a place where you will be safe. What's the use of fighting?

YOUNG SEAL
(ugly chuckle)
Oh, if you're trying to back out, of course I've no more to say.

KOTICK
Will you come with me if I win?

A green light comes into Kotick's eye.

YOUNG SEAL
(carelessly)
Very good. If you win, I'll come.

He has no time to change his mind. Kotick's head is out; teeth sink in the blubber of the young seal's neck. Kotick throws himself back on his haunches, hauls his enemy down the beach, shakes him, knocks him over.

KOTICK
(roaring to the seals)
I've done my best for you these five seasons past. I've found you the island where you'll be safe, but unless your heads are dragged off your silly necks you won't believe. I'm going to teach you now. Look out for yourselves!

He charges into the nurseries—flings himself at the biggest sea catch he can find, catches him by the throat, chokes, bumps, bangs him till he grunts for mercy, throws him aside, attacks the next. His curly white mane stands up with rage; eyes flame; big dog teeth glisten. He has never fasted four months; deep-sea swimming has kept him perfect; he has never fought before.

Old Sea Catch sees him tearing past, hauling grizzled seals about as though they were halibut, upsetting young bachelors in all directions.

SEA CATCH
(roaring)
He may be a fool, but he is the best fighter on the beaches! Don't tackle your father, my son! He's with you!

Kotick roars in answer. Sea Catch waddles in, mustache on end, blowing like a locomotive. Matkah and the seal that will marry Kotick cower down and admire their men-folk.

A gorgeous fight: father and son as long as any seal dares lift a head. When none remain, they parade grandly up and down the beach side by side, bellowing.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - NIGHT

Northern Lights wink and flash through the fog. Kotick climbs a bare rock and looks down on scattered nurseries and torn, bleeding seals.

KOTICK
Now. I've taught you your lesson.

SEA CATCH
(boosting himself up stiffly, fearfully mauled)
My wig! The Killer Whale himself could not have cut them up worse. Son, I'm proud of you, and what's more, I'll come with you to your island—if there is such a place.

KOTICK
(roaring)
Hear you, fat pigs of the sea. Who comes with me to the Sea Cow's tunnel? Answer, or I shall teach you again.

A murmur like the ripple of the tide all up and down the beaches.

SEALS
(thousands of tired voices)
We will come. We will follow Kotick, the White Seal.

Kotick drops his head between his shoulders and shuts his eyes proudly. He is not a white seal any more, but red from head to tail. He scorns to look at or touch one of his wounds.

EXT. WATERS NORTH OF NOVASTOSHNAH - DAY

A week later. Kotick leads his army—nearly ten thousand holluschickie and old seals—away north toward the Sea Cow's tunnel. Seals that stay at Novastoshnah call them idiots from the shore.

EXT. SEA COW BEACHES - DAY

Year upon year, more seals leave Novastoshnah, Lukannon, and the other nurseries for the quiet sheltered beaches. Kotick sits all the summer through, getting bigger and fatter and stronger, while the holluschickie play around him in that sea where no man comes.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Of course it was not all done at once, for the seals are not very clever, and they need a long time to turn things over in their minds. But year after year more seals went away to the quiet, sheltered beaches where Kotick sits all the summer through.

EXT. OPEN SEA - DUSK

Seals swim in a long dark line, heading toward summer beaches. Their voices rise together—a deep-sea song, sad as a national anthem.

SEALS
(singing)
I met my mates in the morning (and, oh, but I am old!)
Where roaring on the ledges the summer ground-swell rolled;
I heard them lift the chorus that drowned the breakers' song—
The Beaches of Lukannon—two million voices strong.

The song of pleasant stations beside the salt lagoons,
The song of blowing squadrons that shuffled down the dunes,
The song of midnight dances that churned the sea to flame—
The Beaches of Lukannon—before the sealers came!

I met my mates in the morning (I'll never meet them more!);
They came and went in legions that darkened all the shore.
And o'er the foam-flecked offing as far as voice could reach
We hailed the landing-parties and we sang them up the beach.

The Beaches of Lukannon—the winter wheat so tall—
The dripping, crinkled lichens, and the sea-fog drenching all!
The platforms of our playground, all shining smooth and worn!
The Beaches of Lukannon—the home where we were born!

I met my mates in the morning, a broken, scattered band.
Men shoot us in the water and club us on the land;
Men drive us to the Salt House like silly sheep and tame,
And still we sing Lukannon—before the sealers came.

Wheel down, wheel down to southward; oh, Gooverooska, go!
And tell the Deep-Sea Viceroys the story of our woe;
Ere, empty as the shark's egg the tempest flings ashore,
The Beaches of Lukannon shall know their sons no more!

EXT. GARDEN PATH - SEGOWLEE CANTONMENT - DAY

Hot sun. A small draggled mongoose lies senseless on the middle of a garden path—fur like a little cat, head and habits like a weasel, eyes and restless nose pink. TEDDY, a small English boy, stands over him. TEDDY'S MOTHER (ALICE) and TEDDY'S FATHER, a big Englishman new to the bungalow, come up.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
This is the story of the great war that Rikki-tikki-tavi fought single-handed, through the bath-rooms of the big bungalow in Segowlee cantonment.

TEDDY
Here's a dead mongoose. Let's have a funeral.

ALICE
No, let's take him in and dry him. Perhaps he isn't really dead.

INT. BUNGALOW SITTING ROOM - DAY

Teddy's Father picks the mongoose up between finger and thumb.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Not dead. Half choked.

They wrap RIKKI-TIKKI in cotton wool and warm him over a little fire. He opens his eyes and sneezes.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Now, don't frighten him, and we'll see what he'll do.

Rikki-tikki looks at the cotton wool, decides it is not good to eat, runs all round the table, sits up, puts his fur in order, scratches himself, and jumps on Teddy's shoulder.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Don't be frightened, Teddy. That's his way of making friends.

TEDDY
Ouch! He's tickling under my chin.

Rikki snuffs at the boy's ear, climbs down, sits rubbing his nose.

ALICE
Good gracious, and that's a wild creature! I suppose he's so tame because we've been kind to him.

TEDDY'S FATHER
All mongooses are like that. If Teddy doesn't pick him up by the tail, or try to put him in a cage, he'll run in and out of the house all day long. Let's give him something to eat.

They feed him raw meat. Rikki-tikki sleeps in Teddy's nursery that night on the boy's pillow.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Rikki-tikki explores: melon beds, roses, a thorn-bush, the long grass. He meets DARZEE the tailor-bird and his wife, fluttering in distress—a fledgling eaten.

DARZEE
A nightmare of a cobra has come into the garden. Nag ate one of our babies yesterday!

From the grass rises NAG, a big black cobra, five feet long, hood spread, eyes like dull hot coals. Beside him, later, NAGAINA his wicked wife.

NAG
I am Nag. The great god Brahm put his mark upon all our people when the first cobra spread his hood to keep the sun off Brahm as he slept. Look, and be afraid!

Rikki-tikki fluffs up, chattering his war-cry—rikki-tikki-tikki-tchik!—but he is young, and Nag is huge. A flap of the hood, a feint; then CHUCHUNDRA the muskrat whispers from the dirt wall that Nag and Nagaina mean to kill the family and hold the bungalow.

INT. BUNGALOW BATHROOM - NIGHT

Rikki-tikki hears a dry slither. Nag has entered through the sluice to wait for Teddy's Father in the morning. Rikki waits on the rim of the water jar. When Nag coils in the dark, Rikki springs, bites deep behind the head, and holds while the great body smashes the room to splinters.

TEDDY'S FATHER (O.S.)
What's that? Who's there?

A shotgun blast. Teddy's Father has fired through the bathroom door. Nag lies dead. Rikki, half deaf, half drowned, staggers out a hero.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Nagaina, mad with grief and rage, plots among the melons. She will kill the family and avenge Nag. Darzee's wife pretends a broken wing and lures Nagaina from her egg-clutch. Rikki smashes egg after egg until one remains.

NAGAINA
Give me the last egg, Rikki-tikki. Give me the last of my eggs, and I will go away and never come back.

RIKKI-TIKKI
On the veranda. The boy is there. Come and take it if you dare!

INT. BUNGALOW VERANDA - DAY

Teddy, Alice, and Teddy's Father sit at breakfast. Nagaina slides onto the veranda stones, hood raised, ready to strike the boy. Rikki dances between, taunting, holding the last egg.

RIKKI-TIKKI
Turn round, Nagaina; turn and fight!

She snatches the egg and flies for the rat-hole by the melon bed. Rikki follows her down into the dark.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Long silence. Then Rikki-tikki crawls out, dusty, triumphant.

RIKKI-TIKKI
It is all over.

Darzee begins a song of praise from the thorn-bush. Rikki, modest and practical, only wants breakfast and a patrol of the garden paths.

INT. TEDDY'S NURSERY - NIGHT

Rikki-tikki lifts his head from Teddy's shoulder. Alice stands in the doorway.

RIKKI-TIKKI
Oh, it's you. What are you bothering for? All the cobras are dead. And if they weren't, I'm here.

He settles again, proud but not too proud, eyes already half shut.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Weeks of sun and rain. Rikki-tikki patrols the paths with tooth and jump and spring and bite—under the roses, along the melon bed, past the thorn-bush where Nagaina died. Never a cobra dares show its head inside the walls.

On the thorn-bush Darzee the tailor-bird swells his throat and sings, tail feathers spread.

DARZEE
Singer and tailor am I—
Doubled the joys that I know—
Proud of my lilt to the sky,
Proud of the house that I sew—
Over and under, so weave I my music—so weave I the house that I sew.

Sing to your fledglings again,
Mother, oh lift up your head!
Evil that plagued us is slain,
Death in the garden lies dead.
Terror that hid in the roses is impotent—flung on the dung-hill and dead!

Who has delivered us, who?
Tell me his nest and his name.
Rikki, the valiant, the true,
Tikki, with eyeballs of flame,
Rikk-tikki-tikki, the ivory-fanged, the hunter with eyeballs of flame!

Give him the Thanks of the Birds,
Bowing with tail feathers spread!
Praise him with nightingale words—
Nay, I will praise him instead.
Hear! I will sing you the praise of the bottle-tailed Rikki, with eyeballs of red!

Rikki-tikki darts out from the grass and chatters up at him. Darzee breaks off mid-note. The rest of the song is lost.

EXT. GARO HILLS - DAY

Mist over ridges. Teak and bamboo. Far below, a river like a steel thread.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I will remember what I was, I am sick of rope and chain—
I will remember my old strength and all my forest affairs.
I will not sell my back to man for a bundle of sugar-cane:
I will go out to my own kind, and the wood-folk in their lairs.

Through the trees moves a great elephant, nearly seventy years old, ten fair feet at the shoulders: KALA NAG—Black Snake—tusks cut short and bound with copper bands. On his neck rides BIG TOOMAI, a weathered mahout; before him on the broad head sits LITTLE TOOMAI, ten years old, four feet high, one rag upon him, sun-bleached brown hair flying.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Kala Nag had served the Indian Government forty-seven years. He had pushed guns from the mud before the Afghan War, carried tents in Upper India, seen the Emperor Theodore dead at Magdala, hauled teak at Moulmein, and stood up to the charge of the wounded tiger. Now he helped catch wild elephants among the Garo hills.

EXT. ELEPHANT CAMP IN THE HILLS - DAY

Brickless lines: elephants picketed to stumps, fodder piled, smoke from cooking fires. Little Toomai scrambles down Kala Nag's trunk and strides up to the great forefeet.

LITTLE TOOMAI
Wah! Thou art a big elephant.

He calls Kala Nag a fat old pig and makes him lift his feet one after the other. Kala Nag obeys without a grumble.

LITTLE TOOMAI
The Government may pay for elephants, but they belong to us mahouts. When thou art old, Kala Nag, some rich rajah will buy thee. Then thou wilt carry gold earrings and a gold howdah, and I shall sit on thy neck with a silver ankus, and men will run before us crying, "Room for the King's elephant!" That will be good, Kala Nag, but not so good as this hunting in the jungles.

BIG TOOMAI
Umph! Thou art a boy, and as wild as a buffalo-calf. This running up and down among the hills is not the best Government service. Give me brick elephant lines, one stall to each elephant, and flat broad roads—instead of this come-and-go camping. Aha, the Cawnpore barracks were good.

Little Toomai says nothing. His eyes are on the misty hills.

EXT. KEDDAH STOCKADE - NIGHT

Torchlight. A stockade of lashed tree-trunks. Wild elephants pour in like boulders in a landslide—trumpeting, crashing, flinging themselves at the posts. Men yell; blank cartridges crack; torches flare.

Kala Nag goes in at the word of command, picks the biggest tusker, hammers and hustles him while drivers rope the smaller ones.

Little Toomai climbs a quivering stockade post, hair flying, a goblin in the torch-light. His high-pitched yells cut through the din.

LITTLE TOOMAI
Mael, mael, Kala Nag! Dant do! Somalo! Somalo! Maro! Mar! Mind the post! Arre! Arre! Hai! Yai! Kya-a-ah!

In a lull he slides down, slips between the elephants, and throws up the loose end of a rope to a driver struggling with a kicking young calf. Kala Nag sees him, catches him in his trunk, and hands him up to Big Toomai. Big Toomai slaps him then and there and puts him back on the post.

EXT. ELEPHANT CAMP IN THE HILLS - DAY

Morning. Big Toomai scolds while Little Toomai hangs his head.

BIG TOOMAI
Are not good brick elephant lines and a little tent carrying enough, that thou must needs go elephant catching on thy own account, little worthless? Now those foolish hunters have spoken to Petersen Sahib of the matter.

LITTLE TOOMAI
What—what will happen?

BIG TOOMAI
Happen! The worst that can happen. Petersen Sahib is a madman. He may even require thee to be an elephant catcher, to sleep in these fever-filled jungles, and at last to be trampled to death in the Keddah. Next week the catching is over, and we of the plains are sent back. But, son, I am angry that thou shouldst meddle in the business that belongs to these dirty Assamese jungle folk. Bad one! Wicked one! Worthless son! Go and wash Kala Nag and attend to his ears, and see that there are no thorns in his feet. Or else Petersen Sahib will surely catch thee and make thee a wild hunter. Bah! Shame! Go!

Little Toomai goes. At Kala Nag's feet he turns up the fringe of the huge right ear and works out a thorn.

LITTLE TOOMAI
No matter. They have said my name to Petersen Sahib, and perhaps—and perhaps—and perhaps—who knows? Hai! That is a big thorn that I have pulled out!

EXT. HILL CAMP UNDER A TREE - DAY

A native clerk at a table pays wages. Drivers take their pay and join the line of elephants ready to start. Catchers and hunters lean on guns and laugh at the plains drivers.

PETERSEN SAHIB lies along the back of his clever she-elephant PUDMINI. MACHUA APPA, the head tracker, speaks undertone to a friend as Big Toomai and Little Toomai approach the clerk.

MACHUA APPA
There goes one piece of good elephant stuff at least. 'Tis a pity to send that young jungle-cock to molt in the plains.

Petersen Sahib turns.

PETERSEN SAHIB
What is that? I did not know of a man among the plains-drivers who had wit enough to rope even a dead elephant.

MACHUA APPA
This is not a man, but a boy. He went into the Keddah at the last drive, and threw Barmao there the rope, when we were trying to get that young calf with the blotch on his shoulder away from his mother.

Machua Appa points. Little Toomai bows to the earth.

PETERSEN SAHIB
He throw a rope? He is smaller than a picket-pin. Little one, what is thy name?

Little Toomai is too frightened to speak. He signs. Kala Nag catches him up in his trunk and holds him level with Pudmini's forehead. Little Toomai covers his face with his hands.

PETERSEN SAHIB
(smiling under his mustache)
Oho! And why didst thou teach thy elephant that trick? Was it to help thee steal green corn from the roofs of the houses when the ears are put out to dry?

LITTLE TOOMAI
Not green corn, Protector of the Poor,—melons.

The men roar with laughter. Little Toomai hangs eight feet up and wishes he were eight feet underground.

BIG TOOMAI
(scowling)
He is Toomai, my son, Sahib. He is a very bad boy, and he will end in a jail, Sahib.

PETERSEN SAHIB
Of that I have my doubts. A boy who can face a full Keddah at his age does not end in jails. See, little one, here are four annas to spend in sweetmeats because thou hast a little head under that great thatch of hair. In time thou mayest become a hunter too.
(more gently)
Remember, though, that Keddahs are not good for children to play in.

LITTLE TOOMAI
(with a big gasp)
Must I never go there, Sahib?

PETERSEN SAHIB
Yes. When thou hast seen the elephants dance. That is the proper time. Come to me when thou hast seen the elephants dance, and then I will let thee go into all the Keddahs.

Another roar of laughter—the old joke that means never. Kala Nag sets Little Toomai down. The boy bows to the earth again.

EXT. HILL PATH TO THE PLAINS - NIGHT

The line of elephants rests. Little Toomai cannot sleep. Kala Nag strains at his picket. From far in the hills comes a sound like a war-drum—elephants calling.

LITTLE TOOMAI
(whispering)
They are going to the dance. Take me with thee, Kala Nag!

He slips the picket. Kala Nag lifts him to his neck and strides into the forest, Pudmini and other old elephants falling in behind, silent as clouds.

EXT. ELEPHANT DANCE CLEARING - NIGHT

A great natural amphitheatre in the Garo hills. Dozens—scores—of wild elephants gather under the stars. They tread a solemn measure, stamping the ground in a circle until the earth is beaten hard and the sound rolls like thunder in the valleys. All night they dance. Little Toomai clings to Kala Nag, eyes wide, the only human child who has ever seen it.

At dawn the host melts into the trees. Kala Nag brings Little Toomai back to camp as the world wakes.

EXT. PETERSEN SAHIB'S CAMP - DAY

Little Toomai leads Petersen Sahib and Machua Appa to the beaten ground—the dance-floor stamped hard as a road. The men stare. Petersen Sahib looks long at the boy.

EXT. PETERSEN SAHIB'S CAMP - NIGHT

The flames die down. Red light of the logs makes the picketed elephants look as though they have been dipped in blood.

MACHUA APPA leaps to his feet with LITTLE TOOMAI held high in the air above his head.

MACHUA APPA
Listen, my brothers. Listen, too, you my lords in the lines there, for I, Machua Appa, am speaking! This little one shall no more be called Little Toomai, but Toomai of the Elephants, as his great-grandfather was called before him. What never man has seen he has seen through the long night, and the favor of the elephant-folk and of the Gods of the Jungles is with him. He shall become a great tracker. He shall become greater than I, even I, Machua Appa! He shall follow the new trail, and the stale trail, and the mixed trail, with a clear eye! He shall take no harm in the Keddah when he runs under their bellies to rope the wild tuskers; and if he slips before the feet of the charging bull elephant, the bull elephant shall know who he is and shall not crush him. Aihai! my lords in the chains—

He whirls up the line of pickets.

MACHUA APPA
—here is the little one that has seen your dances in your hidden places,—the sight that never man saw! Give him honor, my lords! Salaam karo, my children. Make your salute to Toomai of the Elephants! Gunga Pershad, ahaa! Hira Guj, Birchi Guj, Kuttar Guj, ahaa! Pudmini,—thou hast seen him at the dance, and thou too, Kala Nag, my pearl among elephants!—ahaa! Together! To Toomai of the Elephants. Barrao!

At that last wild yell the whole line flings up their trunks till the tips touch their foreheads, and breaks out into the full salute—the crashing trumpet-peal that only the Viceroy of India hears, the Salaamut of the Keddah.

LITTLE TOOMAI stands small among the drivers, forehead marked with jungle-cock blood, as the elephants salute him alone.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But it was all for the sake of Little Toomai, who had seen what never man had seen before—the dance of the elephants at night and alone in the heart of the Garo hills!

INT. ELEPHANT DRIVERS' HUT - NIGHT

A low lamp. TOOMAI'S MOTHER, a young Indian woman in a simple sari, rocks a sleeping baby against her breast. Outside, distant elephant chains clink. She sings soft and clear.

TOOMAI'S MOTHER
Shiv, who poured the harvest and made the winds to blow,
Sitting at the doorways of a day of long ago,
Gave to each his portion, food and toil and fate,
From the King upon the guddee to the Beggar at the gate.
All things made he—Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! He made all,—
Thorn for the camel, fodder for the kine,
And mother's heart for sleepy head, O little son of mine!

She draws the cloth closer about the child.

TOOMAI'S MOTHER
Wheat he gave to rich folk, millet to the poor,
Broken scraps for holy men that beg from door to door;
Battle to the tiger, carrion to the kite,
And rags and bones to wicked wolves without the wall at night.
Naught he found too lofty, none he saw too low—
Parbati beside him watched them come and go;
Thought to cheat her husband, turning Shiv to jest—
Stole the little grasshopper and hid it in her breast.
So she tricked him, Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! Turn and see.
Tall are the camels, heavy are the kine,
But this was Least of Little Things, O little son of mine!

The baby stirs. She smiles and finishes almost in a whisper.

TOOMAI'S MOTHER
When the dole was ended, laughingly she said,
"Master, of a million mouths, is not one unfed?"
Laughing, Shiv made answer, "All have had their part,
Even he, the little one, hidden 'neath thy heart."
From her breast she plucked it, Parbati the thief,
Saw the Least of Little Things gnawed a new-grown leaf!
Saw and feared and wondered, making prayer to Shiv,
Who hath surely given meat to all that live.
All things made he—Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! He made all,—
Thorn for the camel, fodder for the kine,
And mother's heart for sleepy head, O little son of mine!

She kisses the child's hair. The lamp gutters.

EXT. RAWAL PINDI CAMP - DAY

Rain sheets down on a vast military camp—thirty thousand men, camels, elephants, horses, bullocks, and mules gathered for review. Mud roads, tent lines, gun parks. Flags hang heavy and wet.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It had been raining heavily for one whole month—raining on a camp of thirty thousand men and thousands of camels, elephants, horses, bullocks, and mules all gathered together at a place called Rawal Pindi, to be reviewed by the Viceroy of India. He was receiving a visit from the Amir of Afghanistan—a wild king of a very wild country.

Through the murk: the AMIR OF AFGHANISTAN rides with a bodyguard of eight hundred savage men and horses who stare at locomotives and tent-streets as at miracles.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The Amir had brought with him for a bodyguard eight hundred men and horses who had never seen a camp or a locomotive before—savage men and savage horses from somewhere at the back of Central Asia.

EXT. RAWAL PINDI CAMP - NIGHT

Mud and drizzle. Heel-ropes snap. A mob of Afghan horses stampede through the dark between tent ropes. Camels break loose, blunder, fall over guy-lines. Men shout. Canvas heaves.

INT. NARRATOR'S TENT - NIGHT

A modest officer's tent, far from the camel lines. Oil lamp. Waterproof hanging. VIXEN, a sharp fox terrier, white with brown markings, sleeps on a blanket.

A MAN'S HEAD pops through the flap.

CAMP RUNNER
Get out, quick! They're coming! My tent's gone!

NARRATOR—a lean Englishman in shirt-sleeves, period moustache—jams on boots and waterproof. Vixen bolts out the other side.

EXT. NARRATOR'S TENT - NIGHT

Roaring, grunting, bubbling. The tent-pole snaps. The whole tent caves and dances like a mad ghost as a big baggage camel blunders through it.

NARRATOR, wet and angry, cannot help laughing—then runs into the slush, out of sight of the camp lights, plowing through mud.

EXT. ARTILLERY LINES - NIGHT

Stacked cannon in the drizzle. NARRATOR falls over the tail-end of a gun. He spreads his waterproof over one muzzle, props a sort of wigwam with two or three rammers, and lies along the tail of another gun, listening for Vixen.

A jingle of harness. A grunt. BILLY—a tough screw-gun mule, straps and rings and chains on his saddle-pad—passes, shaking wet ears.

Behind him, a BAGGAGE CAMEL: big soft feet squelching and slipping, neck bobbing like a strayed hen's.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
What shall I do? Where shall I go? I have fought with a white thing that waved, and it took a stick and hit me on the neck. Shall we run on?

BILLY
Oh, it was you, you and your friends, that have been disturbing the camp? All right. You'll be beaten for this in the morning. But I may as well give you something on account now.

Harness jingles. Billy backs and catches the camel two kicks in the ribs that ring like a drum.

BILLY
Another time you'll know better than to run through a mule battery at night, shouting "Thieves and fire!" Sit down, and keep your silly neck quiet.

The camel doubles up camel-fashion, like a two-foot rule, and sits down whimpering.

A regular beat of hoofs. TROOP-HORSE—a big Australian cavalry mount, Number Fifteen, E troop, Ninth Lancers—canters up as steadily as on parade, jumps a gun tail, lands close to the mule.

TROOP-HORSE
It's disgraceful. Those camels have racketed through our lines again—the third time this week. How's a horse to keep his condition if he isn't allowed to sleep. Who's here?

BILLY
I'm the breech-piece mule of number two gun of the First Screw Battery, and the other's one of your friends. He's waked me up too. Who are you?

TROOP-HORSE
Number Fifteen, E troop, Ninth Lancers—Dick Cunliffe's horse. Stand over a little, there.

BILLY
Oh, beg your pardon. It's too dark to see much. Aren't these camels too sickening for anything? I walked out of my lines to get a little peace and quiet here.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
(humbly)
My lords, we dreamed bad dreams in the night, and we were very much afraid. I am only a baggage camel of the 39th Native Infantry, and I am not as brave as you are, my lords.

BILLY
Then why didn't you stay and carry baggage for the 39th Native Infantry, instead of running all round the camp?

BAGGAGE CAMEL
They were such very bad dreams. I am sorry. Listen! What is that? Shall we run on again?

BILLY
Sit down, or you'll snap your long stick-legs between the guns.

Billy cocks one ear.

BILLY
Bullocks! Gun bullocks. On my word, you and your friends have waked the camp very thoroughly. It takes a good deal of prodding to put up a gun-bullock.

A chain drags. TWO GUN BULLOCKS plod up, steaming, patient, enormous.

GUN BULLOCK
The camels have waked us. We were dreaming of the thrashing-floor at home. Who is talking?

TROOP-HORSE
Numbers. Cavalry and a mule battery. Your friends the camels have been dancing through the lines.

GUN BULLOCK
They have no manners. Before a review, too. The Viceroy comes tomorrow, and the Amir.

From the dark, a deep soft voice—the ELEPHANT of the gun-team, huge beyond the gun-wheels.

ELEPHANT
I have served forty years, and I have never yet seen a review spoiled by camels. Be still, all of you. There are men listening.

Silence. Then, carefully:

BILLY
Who is the bravest? That is what I want to know. Who does the hardest work?

TROOP-HORSE
Cavalry. We go first into the fire.

BILLY
And we screw-gun mules climb where your big feet cannot. Who brought the guns up the hill at—

GUN BULLOCK
Without us you would have no guns to climb with. We pull when the mud is to the axle.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
And we carry the food that keeps you all alive. Without baggage—

ELEPHANT
(amused rumble)
Peace. Each does his work. I have seen the Afghan guns and the English guns, and the men who ride and the men who walk. Tomorrow the Viceroy and the Amir will look at us all. Stand still in the ranks, and do not disgrace your service. That is the Law.

Vixen creeps under the waterproof to NARRATOR. The animals settle. Rain softens. Far off, a bugle practices for the morning.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And that was all I heard that night among Her Majesty's servants—horse and mule, bullock and camel and elephant—each sure that his own work was the hardest, and each, when the wet dawn came, ready to stand in his place for the great review. So ends the book of the jungle and the camp, of the seal's beach and the mongoose's garden, of the boy who was wolf and the boy who saw the elephants dance. Good hunting to you all, members of the Free People—and good rest.

FADE OUT.

THE END
